crops.description: From California. Seeds presented by James Stewart, La Habra Heights. A fine-flavored South African papaya, pollinized by a plant from the Sandwich Islands.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D.C.
crops.description: From Ceara, Brazil. Seeds collected by H. A. Gardner and presented by the Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D. C., through the Bureau of Chemistry and Soils. A large tropical tree of the Brazilian forests, with rigid leathery oblong leaves 3 to 5 inches long and shining green above. The greenish, ovoid-cylindrical fruits, about 2 inches long, yield an oil known as Oiticica oil, that is used in the paint and varnish industry.

crops.presented_by: Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo (seeds purchased through him)
crops.description: From Chile. Seeds purchased through Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo. A small papaya about 3 1/2 by 4 1/2 inches, with very thin flesh which is highly acid and is used only in making preserves and sirups. The fruit is yellow when ripe with a spicy aromatic flavor and fragrance, but is never eaten fresh.

crops.origin: Santa Maria, near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil
crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.description: From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Santa Maria. A new type of rice developed near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, which develops abnormally large ears and is a heavy yielder.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.description: From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety name: Fronteira.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.description: From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety name: Frondoso.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.description: From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety name: Surpreza.

crops.origin: Jardim Botanico, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil
crops.description: From Brazil. Seeds collected in the Jardim Botanico, Rio de Janeiro, by H. A. Gardner and presented by G. S. Jamieson, Bureau of Chemistry and Soils. For previous introduction and description see 106347.

crops.origin: East Africa (collected on the road between Ressano Garcia and Lourenço Marques, Mozambique)
crops.description: From East Africa. Seeds collected by Mrs. Thomas Barbour on the road between Ressano Garcia and Lourenço Marques, Mozambique. The "sausage tree" of eastern tropical Africa becomes 30 to 50 feet high, with rough ternate leaves made up of seven to nine elliptic-oblong leaflets; the large claret-colored flowers are in long spikes, and the blunt sausagelike fruits are 12 to 18 inches long.

crops.presented_by: F. H. Brunning Pty. Ltd., Melbourne
crops.description: From Australia. Seeds presented by F. H. Brunning Pty. Ltd., Melbourne. Variety: Dwalganup. An extra early strain.

crops.presented_by: F. H. Brunning Pty. Ltd., Melbourne
crops.description: From Australia. Seeds presented by F. H. Brunning Pty. Ltd., Melbourne. Variety: Wenigup. A late clover.

From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2488. A tropical shrub with thick leathery oval-elliptic dark-green leaves and small white flowers in large terminal cymes. It is native to Brazil. For the introduction of plants see 106371.

crops.origin: British Guiana (native to sandy places in British Guiana)
crops.description: From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2483. Garuru. A handsome tree with leathery elliptic leaves shining green above and 4 to 6 inches long and large yellow flowers. Native to sandy places in British Guiana. For the introduction of plants see 106372.
From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2493. A cultivated variety of common redpepper.

crops.origin: British Guiana (native to northern South America)
crops.description: From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2490. Cuttings of a large tropical tree with opposite digitately 3- to 5-foliolate leathery leaves, large greenish flowers, and hard-shelled nuts with white edible kernels. Native to northern South America.

From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2478. Cuttings from a small tree of rather straggly habit with golden-yellow flowers in loose racemes. For previous introduction see 97567.

crops.origin: British Guiana (collected at Bartica, on the Essequiba River)
crops.description: From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2491. A cultivated watermelon collected at Bartica, on the Essequiba River.
From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2449. Bulbs of cultivated plants collected at Mazaruni Station.
From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2450. Bulbs of cultivated plants.
From British Guiana. Material collected by W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry. No. 2480. Kanakudiballi.
